\section{Core Assumptions of TRSM}
\subsection{The Backward Arow of Time }
Time is postulated to be a past--directed dimension that is \emph{generated at the instant an event occurs}, records the event step by step, and then propagates backward as a reflected flow archiving negative--valued entries. This reflective, recording nature of time is the main reason that led to the emergence of our secondary, reflective echoes-universe.   

\subsection{Dual-Universe Structure}
The cosmological existence comprises two parallel universes:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Advanced Positive-Energy Universe:} Located on the positive time axis, continuously evolving toward the future. This advanced universe has special physical properties and free of any time limits or temporal restrictions.
    \item \textbf{Our Reflected Negative-Energy Universe:} Located on the negative time axis, representing a temporal reflection of the advanced universe. This reflected time records events as a negative, temporal values  creating a cosmic historical archive of the advanced universe and a reflected echoes-universe of it.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Fundamental Negative Temporal Background (Dark Energy)}
The reflected, negative-energy, temporal-environment "identified as dark energy" constitutes the fundamental homogeneous fabric of our reflected universe. This negative temporal spectrum is the primordial structure from which all mass, energy, and cosmological phenomena emerge in our universe.

\subsection{Dual Reflected Temporal Vectors}
Within a negative temporal-background, every event in our universe arises from a pair of temporal vectors:
\begin{itemize}
    \item The first temporal vector  is the vector of temporal background "dark energy" which reflected directly from the advanced universe. This vector moves at the speed of light but, in the opposite direction taken a negative values.
    \item The second vector is reflected from the structure of the new emerging universe. This vector is produced at the moment the event occurs. It records the event and then is reflected back in parallel with the first vector forming a second layer of the reflected time fabric, which, along with the first fabric forming what we know as "dark matter".
\end{itemize}
