\section{Light as a Measure of Temporal Flow Velocity}

In this negative temporal environment, the speed of light is redefined as follows:

\begin{itemize}
    \item Light is not merely a conventional particle or wave but rather a measure of the flow velocity of temporal vectors in the negative temporal environment.
    \item The maximum reflected temporal speed equals the speed of light, but in the opposite direction (negative).
\end{itemize}

When a particle increases its velocity moving along the negative temporal axis toward zero, the reflected temporal vector slows and dilates time until it completely vanishes upon reaching the speed of light:

\begin{equation}
T \rightarrow 0 \quad \text{as} \quad v \rightarrow c
\end{equation}

Conversely, as particle velocity decreases towards absolute zero, the speed of the reflected temporal vector reaches its maximum negative value, initiating temporal deposition into mass:

\begin{equation}
T \rightarrow T_{max(-c)} \quad \text{as} \quad v \rightarrow 0
\end{equation}

Mass is thus created from negative temporal energy through temporal deposition at low velocities.

\section{Universal Dual-Vector Temporal Flow Equation (UTFE)}

Every cosmological event must adhere to the fundamental equation:

\begin{equation}
(v_T^{+})^2 + (v_T^{-})^2 = c^2
\end{equation}

where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $v_T^{+}$ represents the second layer of temporal flow speed vector which is reflected from the act of building the secondary reflected universe that we live in. This vector is moving toward zero and positive values within the basic, negative fabric of reflected spectrum determine by the initial vector $v_T^{-}$.
    \item $v_T^{-}$ represents the basic, negative, spectral fabric witch is reflected from an advanced universe. This reflected temporal flow speed vector moving toward negative time values ( from future backward to past).
    \item $c$ is the maximum temporal speed magnitude equivalent to the speed of light.
\end{itemize}
