\section{TRSM Unified Cycle--Time Identity}
\label{sec:TRSM-unified-identity}

For any coherent excitation (mode) with energy $E$ we use
\begin{equation}
E=\hbar\omega=h\nu,
\qquad
T_{\mathrm{eff}}=\frac{E}{k_B},
\qquad
m_{\mathrm{eff}}=\frac{E}{c^2},
\end{equation}
and define the \emph{cycle time} (phase period)
\begin{equation}
\boxed{\;
\tau_{\mathrm{cyc}}
=\frac{1}{\nu}
=\frac{h}{E}
=\frac{h}{k_B T_{\mathrm{eff}}}
=\frac{h}{m_{\mathrm{eff}}c^2}
\;}
\label{eq:TRSM-unified-cycle}
\end{equation}
Within TRSM, the negative-time accumulation for a branch can be identified with a cycle time, e.g.
\begin{equation}
\Delta t^{-}\;\equiv\;\tau_{\mathrm{cyc}}^{(-)}=\frac{h}{E^{(-)}},
\end{equation}
whenever the branch is probed as a coherent mode. This identity is definitional at the mode level (not a universal equality across arbitrary thermodynamic or inertial states) and provides a consistent bridge between frequency, effective temperature, effective mass, and temporal periodicity in TRSM.

 
\section{Reflected Temporal Fabric and Emergent Structure in TRSM}
\label{sec:TRSM-fabric}

(Foundational postulate)
The Temporal Reflected Spectrum Model (TRSM) posits that \emph{dark energy} is a negative-time reflected spectrum sourced by an advanced positive universe. This spectrum establishes a cold, negative-time primordial fabric, denoted by $\mathcal{F}^{-}$, within which additional negative-time reflections accumulate over negative time $\Delta t^{-}$ and deposit as rigid primordial quanta. Over cosmological durations these deposits condense into atoms and then heavy elements, with higher heavy-element abundance in older/colder regions.


\paragraph{Organization.}
Every event in our universe is initiated within $\mathcal{F}^{-}$. Each \emph{reflected temporal seed} nucleates a \emph{negative-time helical wave} with two branches: an inward (compressive) branch and an outward (expanding) branch, both carrying negative-time character. A locally positive effective energy appears only upon \emph{inner-branch squaring} (phase-aligned squaring on the inward branch), which releases heat, energy and radiation.
\subsection{Iron pivot for cold deposition vs.\ warm decay.}
We adopt a nuclear pivot at the iron–nickel peak,
\[
E_{\rm piv}^{(N)}\simeq 8.8~\mathrm{MeV},\quad 
\tau_{\rm Fe}^{(N)}=\frac{h}{E_{\rm piv}^{(N)}}\approx 4.7\times10^{-22}\,\mathrm{s},\quad
T_{\rm Fe}^{(N)}=\frac{E_{\rm piv}^{(N)}}{k_B}\approx 1.0\times10^{11}\,\mathrm{K}.
\]
Cold temporal deposition dominates when $\tau_{\rm cyc}\gtrsim\tau_{\rm Fe}^{(N)}$, while warm decay (heavy$\to$light transmutation) sets in for $\tau_{\rm cyc}\lesssim\tau_{\rm Fe}^{(N)}$.
An equivalent vorticity threshold follows from
\[
\eta_\omega f^{2}\rho_T\,\omega_c^{2}\sim n_B\,\frac{B}{A}\,\frac{1}{\tau_{\rm cyc}}
\ \Rightarrow\ 
\omega_c\approx\sqrt{\frac{n_B(B/A)}{\eta_\omega f^{2}\rho_T\,\tau_{\rm cyc}}}.
\]
For laboratory anchoring we also note the $^{57}\mathrm{Fe}$ Mössbauer line ($E_\gamma=14.4$ keV), with
$\tau_{\rm Fe}^{(\gamma)}=h/E_\gamma\approx2.9\times10^{-19}$ s, as a precise UTFE spectral standard.

\subsection{Temporal Sedimentation and Heavy-Nucleus Genesis (TRSM)}

\paragraph*{Setup and maximized deposition in the cold epoch.}
In the primordial cold reflected fabric (single active layer), local positive energy deposition is
\begin{equation}
\rho_{+}(x;\beta)=\kappa\,f^{2}\,\rho_T(x)\left(\frac{v_{T,1}^{-}}{c}\right)^{2},
\qquad f\equiv E_{\rm cut},\ \ \rho_T\equiv|\Phi|^{2}.
\label{eq:dep-law}
\end{equation}
In the pre-vortical regime one has $T\simeq 0$, $\beta\simeq 0$, hence $v_{T,1}^{-}\to c$ and
\begin{equation}
\rho_{+}^{\max}(x)=\kappa\,f^{2}\,\rho_T(x),\qquad 
\rho_m^{\max}(x)=\frac{\rho_{+}^{\max}(x)}{c^{2}}.
\end{equation}
This sets the stage for \emph{temporal sedimentation}: negative-time reflections condense into rigid, low-entropy deposits.

\paragraph*{Nucleation criterion (single-layer background).}
Let $R\equiv|\Phi|$ and define an effective free-energy functional on spatial slices orthogonal to $u^\mu$,
